column1:
Consider the following pseudocode for building a noun-relationship graph:<br><pre>NounGraph = CreateEmptyGraph()
NounsList = GetNounsFromParagraph()
for each sentence in Paragraph:
NounsInSentence = GetNounsFromSentence(sentence)
for each pair (N1, N2) in NounsInSentence:
if IsConnectedByVerb(N1, N2):
AddEdge(NounGraph, N1, N2)
Return NounGraph</pre>What is a primary limitation of this simplified procedure?<ul><li>a) It processes the paragraph sentence by sentence, which is inefficient.</li><li>b) It incorrectly adds edges based on verb connections.</li><li>c) It fails to establish connections across sentence boundaries via pronouns.</li><li>d) It should not initialize an empty graph at the beginning.</li></ul>;"Correct: c)";"<b>Explanation:</b> This procedure only checks for connections between nouns that appear within the same sentence. It completely misses the critical step of resolving pronouns to nouns from previous sentences
